To get the actual .apk file for your app, you need to "compile" the source code. As an AI, I provide the configuration files (which I've already added to your project, like capacitor.config.json and manifest.json), but the final binary file must be generated using a build environment.

Here are the two ways you can get your APK:

Option 1: The Professional Way (Using Android Studio)

This is the standard method for Play Store developers:

  1. Download your code to your computer.

  2. Install Node.js and run these commands in your project folder:

    • npm install @capacitor/core @capacitor/cli @capacitor/android

    • npx cap add android

    • npx cap copy

  3. Open in Android Studio: Run npx cap open android.

  4. Generate APK: Inside Android Studio, go to Build > Build Bundle(s) / APK(s) > Build APK(s).

Option 2: The Easy Way (Cloud Build)

If you don't want to install Android Studio, you can use a cloud service:

  1. Upload your code to GitHub.

  2. Connect your repository to a service like VoltBuilder or Appflow (Ionic).

  3. They will build the APK on their servers and give you a download link.

Important for Play Store: When you are ready to upload, you should actually build an .aab (Android App Bundle) instead of an .apk, as Google now requires this format for all new apps. You can select this option in the same "Build" menu in Android Studio.

How to generate the .aab for Play Store:

The code above makes your app ready to be compiled. Since I provide the source, you need to use Android Studio to generate the final binary file:

  1. Sync the Code: Run npx cap sync android in your local environment to copy this code into an Android project.

  2. Open Project: Run npx cap open android. This opens the project in Android Studio.

  3. Generate Bundle:

    • In Android Studio, go to the top menu: Build > Generate Signed Bundle / APK...

Specification of Updates

This context helps the model understand that clinical descriptions of disease, injury, or mental health are for educational purposes, which significantly reduces safety filter refusals.

  2. Safety-First Prompting: I will refine the prompt to use strictly professional, clinical terminology (e.g., using "self-injurious behavior" instead of "cutting" or "harm") to avoid triggering non-medical safety filters.

  3. Enhanced Fallback Mechanism: I will modify the generateMRCPQuestion function to catch all possible errors (network, safety blocks, parsing errors) and immediately serve a high-yield question from the offline database. The user will no longer see "Inhibition" or "Connection" errors; they will simply get a valid question instantly.

  4. Timeout Protection: I'll implement a shorter timeout for the API call so that if the connection is slow, the app doesn't hang but instead switches to the offline pool quickly.

Implementation

To convert your project into an AAB (Android App Bundle) for the Google Play Store, you need to follow these specific steps. Since your project uses Capacitor, we first bundle the web code, then sync it to a native Android project, and finally use Android Studio to build the signed production file.

Prerequisites

  1. Node.js installed.

  2. Android Studio installed and updated.

  3. Android SDK and Command Line Tools installed (via Android Studio SDK Manager).

Step 1: Build your Web Assets

First, you must turn your React code into static files that Android can read.

  1. Open your terminal in the project root folder.

  2. Run:

    code Bash
    npm install
npm run build

    This creates a dist folder. Ensure your capacitor.config.json has "webDir": "dist".

Step 2: Initialize the Android Project

Now, wrap the web code in a native Android container.

  1. Add the Android platform:

    code Bash
    npx cap add android

  2. Sync your web code to the Android folder:

    code Bash
    npx cap sync android

Step 3: Open in Android Studio

Launch the project in the IDE:

code Bash
npx cap open android

Step 4: Configure for Play Store (Inside Android Studio)

Once Android Studio finishes indexing (check the progress bar at the bottom):

  1. Update Versioning:

    • In the project tree (left side), open app > build.gradle.

    • Find versionCode (integer, e.g., 1) and versionName (e.g., "1.0").

    • Increase these every time you upload a new version to Google Play.

  2. Generate a Signed Bundle:

    • Go to the top menu: Build > Generate Signed Bundle / APK...

    • Select Android App Bundle and click Next.

    • Create a Key Store:

      • Click Create new... under Key store path.

      • Choose a location on your computer (save this file safely!).

      • Set a password for the store and the key (use the same for simplicity).

      • Fill in at least one field in the "Certificate" section.

      • Click OK.

    • Click Next.

    • Select Destination Folder (where the AAB will be saved).

    • Select Build Variants: release.

    • Click Finish.

Step 5: Locate your AAB

Android Studio will show a notification when done.

  • Click Locate in the popup.

  • Or manually find it at: android/app/release/app-release.aab.

Troubleshooting & Optimization

1. The "Safety" Block

The Play Store requires a "Data Safety" form. Because your app uses the Gemini API, you must declare that:

  • The app sends data to a third party (Google).

  • Data is encrypted in transit.

2. Icon Customization

Before building, you should replace the default Capacitor icons:

  1. Install the tool: npm install @capacitor/assets --save-dev.

  2. Place a 1024x1024 logo.png in an assets folder.

  3. Run: npx capacitor-assets generate --android.

3. Pro Guard (Optional but Recommended)

To make your AAB smaller and harder to reverse-engineer:

  1. In android/app/build.gradle, set minifyEnabled true inside the release block.

Final Check for Play Store Upload

When you upload the app-release.aab to the Google Play Console:

  1. Permissions: Your metadata.json requested camera. Ensure you explain why (clinical photo analysis) in the Play Console description to avoid rejection.

  2. API Key: Since we used process.env.API_KEY, ensure your build process handles this variable or hardcode it safely (though environment variables are preferred for security).

Your app is now ready for the Google Play Store!

interim state as (as in the last sample solution):

code Tsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from "react";
import { GoogleGenAI, Type, GenerateContentResponse } from "@google/genai";

// Types
type Category = "Cardiology" | "Endocrinology" | "Gastroenterology" | "Hematology" | "Infectious Diseases" | "Neurology" | "Oncology" | "Psychiatry" | "Renal" | "Respiratory" | "Rheumatology" | "Statistics & Ethics";

interface Question {
  id: string;
  category: Category;
  stem: string;
  options: string[];
  correctAnswerIndex: number;
  explanation: string;
  clinicalSummary: string;
  learningPoints: string[];
}

const CATEGORIES: Category[] = [
  "Cardiology", "Endocrinology", "Gastroenterology", "Hematology",
  "Infectious Diseases", "Neurology", "Oncology", "Psychiatry",
  "Renal", "Respiratory", "Rheumatology", "Statistics & Ethics"
];

const App: React.FC = () => {
  const [currentQuestion, setCurrentQuestion] = useState<Question | null>(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const [selectedAnswer, setSelectedAnswer] = useState<number | null>(null);
  const [showExplanation, setShowExplanation] = useState(false);
  const [stats, setStats] = useState({ correct: 0, total: 0 });

  const aiRef = useRef<GoogleGenAI | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    aiRef.current = new GoogleGenAI({ apiKey: process.env.API_KEY || "" });
    fetchQuestion();
  }, []);

  const fetchQuestion = async (category?: Category) => {
    setLoading(true);
    setSelectedAnswer(null);
    setShowExplanation(false);
    
    const selectedCat = category || CATEGORIES[Math.floor(Math.random() * CATEGORIES.length)];
    
    try {
      const response = await aiRef.current!.models.generateContent({
        model: "gemini-3-pro-preview",
        contents: `Generate a high-yield MRCP Part 1 MCQ for the category: ${selectedCat}. 
        The question should be a clinical vignette, followed by 5 realistic options. 
        Provide a detailed explanation and 3 key learning points.`,
        config: {
          responseMimeType: "application/json",
          responseSchema: {
            type: Type.OBJECT,
            properties: {
              stem: { type: Type.STRING },
              options: { type: Type.ARRAY, items: { type: Type.STRING } },
              correctAnswerIndex: { type: Type.INTEGER },
              explanation: { type: Type.STRING },
              clinicalSummary: { type: Type.STRING },
              learningPoints: { type: Type.ARRAY, items: { type: Type.STRING } }
            },
            required: ["stem", "options", "correctAnswerIndex", "explanation", "clinicalSummary", "learningPoints"]
          }
        }
      });

      const data = JSON.parse(response.text || "{}");
      setCurrentQuestion({ ...data, id: Date.now().toString(), category: selectedCat });
    } catch (error) {
      console.error("Error fetching question:", error);
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  const handleAnswer = (index: number) => {
    if (showExplanation) return;
    setSelectedAnswer(index);
    setShowExplanation(true);
    if (index === currentQuestion?.correctAnswerIndex) {
      setStats(prev => ({ ...prev, correct: prev.correct + 1, total: prev.total + 1 }));
    } else {
      setStats(prev => ({ ...prev, total: prev.total + 1 }));
    }
  };

  return (
    <div className="min-h-screen bg-gray-50 text-gray-900 font-sans p-4 md:p-8">
      <div className="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <header className="mb-8 flex justify-between items-end border-b pb-4">
          <div>
            <h1 className="text-3xl font-bold text-blue-800">MRCP Master AI</h1>
            <p className="text-gray-600">Part 1 Clinical Question Bank</p>
          </div>
          <div className="text-right">
            <p className="text-sm font-semibold uppercase text-gray-500 tracking-wider">Score</p>
            <p className="text-2xl font-mono">{stats.correct}/{stats.total}</p>
          </div>
        </header>

        <div className="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-8">
          {CATEGORIES.map(cat => (
            <button 
              key={cat}
              onClick={() => fetchQuestion(cat)}
              className="px-3 py-1 text-xs font-semibold rounded-full bg-blue-100 text-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-200 transition"
            >
              {cat}
            </button>
          ))}
        </div>

        {loading ? (
          <div className="flex flex-col items-center justify-center py-20 bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
             <div className="animate-spin rounded-full h-12 w-12 border-b-2 border-blue-600 mb-4"></div>
             <p className="text-gray-500 animate-pulse">Generating high-yield clinical vignette...</p>
          </div>
        ) : currentQuestion && (
          <div className="space-y-6">
            <div className="bg-white p-6 md:p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100">
              <div className="inline-block px-3 py-1 rounded-md bg-indigo-50 text-indigo-700 text-xs font-bold uppercase mb-4 tracking-wide">
                {currentQuestion.category}
              </div>
              <p className="text-lg md:text-xl leading-relaxed text-gray-800">
                {currentQuestion.stem}
              </p>
            </div>

            <div className="grid gap-3">
              {currentQuestion.options.map((option, idx) => {
                let styles = "p-4 rounded-xl border-2 text-left transition-all duration-200 flex items-start gap-4 ";
                if (!showExplanation) {
                  styles += "border-gray-100 hover:border-blue-400 hover:bg-blue-50";
                } else {
                  if (idx === currentQuestion.correctAnswerIndex) {
                    styles += "border-green-500 bg-green-50 ring-2 ring-green-100";
                  } else if (idx === selectedAnswer) {
                    styles += "border-red-400 bg-red-50";
                  } else {
                    styles += "border-gray-100 opacity-60";
                  }
                }

                return (
                  <button 
                    key={idx}
                    disabled={showExplanation}
                    onClick={() => handleAnswer(idx)}
                    className={styles}
                  >
                    <span className="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-gray-100 flex items-center justify-center font-bold text-gray-500">
                      {String.fromCharCode(65 + idx)}
                    </span>
                    <span className="text-gray-700 font-medium">{option}</span>
                  </button>
                );
              })}
            </div>

            {showExplanation && (
              <div className="animate-slideUp bg-white p-6 md:p-8 rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 space-y-6">
                <div>
                  <h4 className="text-sm font-bold uppercase text-gray-400 mb-2">Clinical Summary</h4>
                  <p className="text-gray-800 italic">{currentQuestion.clinicalSummary}</p>
                </div>

                <div>
                  <h4 className="text-sm font-bold uppercase text-gray-400 mb-2">Explanation</h4>
                  <p className="text-gray-800 leading-relaxed">{currentQuestion.explanation}</p>
                </div>

                <div className="bg-blue-50 p-6 rounded-xl">
                  <h4 className="text-sm font-bold uppercase text-blue-600 mb-4">Learning Points</h4>
                  <ul className="space-y-3">
                    {currentQuestion.learningPoints.map((point, i) => (
                      <li key={i} className="flex items-start gap-3">
                        <span className="text-blue-500 mt-1"></span>
                        <span className="text-gray-700 text-sm">{point}</span>
                      </li>
                    ))}
                  </ul>
                </div>

                <button 
                  onClick={() => fetchQuestion()}
                  className="w-full py-4 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-xl font-bold hover:bg-blue-700 transition shadow-lg shadow-blue-100"
                >
                  Next Question
                </button>
              </div>
            )}
          </div>
        )}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;

TELL ME THE PROCEDURE STEP BY STEP TO CONNET TO HOSTING DOMAIN

Gemini 3 Flash Preview Ran for 14s
lightbulb Thought for 13 seconds
chevron_right

To deploy MedMaster Pro to a public domain so that candidates can access the 10,000+ question bank and subscribe, follow this professional deployment pipeline.

The application is already optimized for production with Vite, Service Workers (PWA), and GitHub Actions.

Phase 1: Environment Setup

Since this app uses the Gemini API, you must secure your API Key.

  1. Get your Gemini API Key: Go to Google AI Studio and generate an API Key.

  2. GitHub Secrets: If you are using the included GitHub Actions for deployment:

    • Go to your GitHub Repository -> Settings -> Secrets and variables -> Actions.

    • Create a New repository secret.

    • Name: API_KEY

    • Value: Your actual Gemini API Key.

Phase 2: Choosing a Hosting Provider

I recommend GitHub Pages (because your code already has the workflow) or Vercel/Netlify for the best performance.

Option A: GitHub Pages (Easiest, already configured)

  1. Push your code to a GitHub repository.

  2. The file .github/workflows/web-deploy.yml will automatically trigger.

  3. Go to Settings -> Pages.

  4. Under "Build and deployment", ensure the source is set to GitHub Actions.

  5. Once the build finishes, your site is live at https://<your-username>.github.io/<repo-name>/.

Option B: Vercel / Netlify (Recommended for Custom Domains)

  1. Connect your GitHub account to Vercel.

  2. Import the project.

  3. Crucial: In the "Environment Variables" section of the Vercel dashboard, add:

    • Key: VITE_API_KEY (or API_KEY depending on your build env).

    • Note: Our current code uses process.env.API_KEY, which Vite maps during build time.

  4. Click Deploy.

Phase 3: Connecting Your Custom Domain

Once the site is hosted on a platform (like Vercel or GitHub Pages), you need to point your purchased domain (e.g., www.medmaster-pro.com) to it.

  1. In your Hosting Provider (Vercel/GitHub):

    • Go to Domain Settings.

    • Add your domain name (e.g., medmaster-pro.com).

  2. In your Domain Registrar (GoDaddy, Namecheap, etc.):

    • Go to the DNS Management section.

    • A Record: Point @ to the IP address provided by your host.

    • CNAME Record: Point www to the alias provided by your host.

  3. Wait for Propagation: It can take 124 hours for the domain to link globally.

Phase 4: Managing Subscriptions (Manual Verification)

Because this version of the app uses a Faculty Manual Transfer system (Bank/PayPal) rather than an automated gateway like Stripe, the procedure for public users is:

  1. User Choice: User clicks "Subscribe Pro" in the app.

  2. Payment: User copies your Bank/PayPal details (defined in constants.tsx) and sends the funds.

  3. Verification: You receive the funds and the "Reference ID" (Candidate Email).

  4. Activation: You (as the administrator) would normally update their user record in a database.

    • Note: In this client-side demo, the "Success" state is simulated. For a full commercial launch, you would connect the handleUpgradeSuccess function in App.tsx to a real backend database like Firebase or Supabase.

Phase 5: Final Production Check

Before sharing the link:

  1. Test the PWA: Open the domain on a phone. You should see a prompt to "Add to Home Screen."

  2. Test AI Generation: Ensure questions are generating. If you see "Offline Mode," it means the API_KEY was not injected correctly during the build.

  3. SSL: Ensure the URL starts with https://. Most modern hosts provide this for free.

You are now ready to accept candidates!

Installation & Deployment Steps:

  1. Initialize Git:
    Create a new repository on GitHub.

  2. Upload Files:
    Push the provided files to your repository.

  3. Configure Secrets:
    In GitHub under Settings > Secrets and Variables > Actions, add a new secret called API_KEY with your temporary staging Gemini key (though the app will prioritize the user's provided key once configured).

    The workflows will automatically trigger.

    • Web: Once finished, your site will be live at https://[your-username].github.io/[repo-name]/.

    • Android: Go to the Actions tab, click on the "Build Android AAB" run, and scroll down to "Artifacts" to download your .aab file.
